"CORE_NARRATIVE: Current light field depth estimation is fundamentally bottlenecked by the single Lambertian assumption, which fails to capture the diverse physical realities of specular and scattering interactions. By establishing a unified physical framework via dual-mask modulation and MRI-inspired angular frequency analysis, we mathematically decode these complex light-matter interactions at the pixel level. This paradigm shift transforms depth estimation from a heuristic patchwork into a physically grounded solution for complex real-world scenes.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open with a striking conceptual contrast between the idealized Lambertian world assumed by current algorithms and the physically complex reality of urban scenes, where unmodeled specular and scattering interactions cause Epipolar Plane Image (EPI) structures to catastrophically collapse.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Highlight that while existing methods attempt to heuristically mask or filter out non-Lambertian EPI violations, they fail because they treat the symptoms rather than the physical root causes of surface roughness and wavevector deflection. This critical gap necessitates our transition from empirical patching to a principled, unified physical modeling approach driven by Radiance Tensor Field (RTF) rank analysis.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the dual-mask design as the direct mathematical instantiation of physical surface roughness and wavevector deflection, while the MRI-inspired angular FFT provides the computationally efficient mechanism to decode these properties from sparse angular samples. Every architectural choice is explicitly mapped to resolving a specific physical violation of the Lambertian assumption, ensuring the model inherently understands mixed-material scenes.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Structure the experiments to not only demonstrate superior depth accuracy in non-Lambertian regions, but also explicitly validate the underlying physical claims through material classification metrics (AUC > 0.90) and RTF rank distribution analysis. Ablation studies must definitively prove that removing the physical masks degrades performance specifically in specular and scattering areas, confirming the necessity of the unified framework.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Reiterate that transcending the Lambertian assumption via a unified physical framework is not merely an incremental algorithmic tweak, but a fundamental resolution to the root causes of depth estimation failures in complex scenes. Conclude by projecting how this physically grounded, dual-mask paradigm can generalize to broader computational imaging and rendering tasks beyond depth estimation."